There are currently no approved vaccines or medicines that can cure Ebola. However, there are several experimental therapies and drugs in development that show promising results in clinical trials:

    Favipiravir (T705) - An antiviral drug originally developed for influenza treatment that has shown some effectiveness against Ebola in early studies. It works by inhibiting viral RNA synthesis.

    ZMapp - A cocktail of three different medications created specifically for Ebola treatment that has been used on a small number of patients in West Africa. While it shows initial promise, its efficacy and safety have yet to be fully determined.

    Chloroquine and azithromycin - Two antibiotics commonly used to treat infections that may also show promise against Ebola. Chloroquine blocks virus entry into cells while azithromycin disrupts virus reproduction inside host cells. Both compounds have been used on compassionate grounds since September 2014 when they were granted emergency use authorization from regulatory agencies in both Europe and the United States.

    Edmonston-Zea B vaccine - This Ebola vaccine was first developed during the 2014 outbreak but never made it to clinical trials before being rushed into production after cases surged again this year. In July 2019, WHO recommended the vaccine for all frontline healthcare workers dealing with suspected Ebola outbreaks in Guinea, Sierra Leone, and Liberia.

Ebola can cause severe illness and death due to internal and external bleeding, organ failure, and other complications. The disease primarily spreads through direct contact with bodily fluids such as blood, saliva, vomit, and feces. Prevention measures include avoiding contact with infected individuals, practicing good hygiene like hand washing, wearing protective clothing and equipment like gloves and masks, and following public health guidelines like isolating sick people and handling bodies safely.

Sure, here are 5 steps that can help reduce the amount of stress involved in filing your taxes:

Start early: Begin preparing your tax return well before April 15th so you have plenty of time to gather all necessary documents and data.

Use online tools: There are many free and paid tax preparation software programs available on the internet that can guide you through the process step by step.

Hire a professional: If you feel comfortable doing it yourself but still want someone else to take care of it, consider hiring a tax preparer who specializes in helping individuals like you.

Keep track of important information: Make sure you keep all relevant tax forms, receipts, and other documentation handy while working on your tax return so you don't miss any crucial details.

Break down large tasks into smaller ones: Large projects can be overwhelming, especially when dealing with complicated tax laws and regulations. Try breaking down larger tasks into smaller, more manageable pieces to make them easier to complete.

By following these tips, you can significantly reduce the amount of stress associated with filing your taxes and ensure a smoother experience overall.
